#speculation(title: [The HIV/AIDS Food Assistance Template: Precedented Model for ME/CFS])[
The HIV/AIDS food insecurity literature provides a directly applicable template: in HIV, food insecurity is now recognized as a modifiable disease determinant, with food assistance integrated into standard clinical care pathways. ME/CFS shares identical disease→employment loss→food insecurity risk pathways but has zero clinical integration of food access support. (Certainty: 0.65; Origin: brainstorm)

*Cross-disease evidence.*
In HIV, food insecurity independently predicts incomplete viral suppression, CD4+ T-cell decline, metabolic complications, and mortality @weiser2011foodinsecurityhiv. Food assistance interventions (medically tailored meals, clinic-based food pantries) improve CD4+ counts, medication adherence, and clinical outcomes @palar2015foodassistancehiv @palar2018mtmhiv. The HIV SDoH literature is approximately 15 years ahead of ME/CFS on this dimension.

*Applicability to ME/CFS.*
The structural parallels are direct: chronic disease → employment loss (Bowden 2026: 18.3% ME/CFS employment vs. 83.8% general population) → income reduction → food insecurity → nutritional deficiency → worsened disease outcomes. Lin 2025 (aOR 1.73 for FI→Long COVID) and Datta 2025 (1–11 percentage-point FI increase across income strata) support the same directional pattern for post-infectious chronic illness. SNAP participation attenuated the FI→Long COVID association (Lin 2025, p-interaction=0.04), directly paralleling HIV food assistance findings.

*Implementation.*
HIV-style food assistance integration for ME/CFS would include: clinic-based food insecurity screening at intake (validated 2-question Hunger Vital Sign), automatic SNAP enrollment assistance, on-site food pantry or MTM referrals, and adapted food programs for housebound patients (delivery, minimal preparation requirements). The HIV precedent demonstrates feasibility and suggests effect sizes: clinic-based food programs typically achieve 40–60% food insecurity prevalence reduction among attendees.

*Limitations.*
The HIV template is precedented but not directly tested in ME/CFS. HIV has well-characterized biological pathways (CD4+ monitoring, viral load) that make nutritional effects measurable; ME/CFS lacks equivalent gold-standard outcomes. MTM programs are resource-intensive and may not be scalable without dedicated funding. Zero ME/CFS food assistance intervention studies exist.

*Falsifiable prediction.*
If HIV-style food assistance integration (FI screening + SNAP enrollment assistance + MTM referral) is implemented in ME/CFS clinics, FI prevalence among clinic attendees will decline by ≥30% and SF-36 physical function scores will improve by ≥5 points relative to standard-care controls within 12 months. Falsified if food access improves without corresponding functional improvement, or if FI prevalence remains unchanged despite intervention.

*Consequence:* HIV clinicians integrated food assistance into standard care 15 years ago because they saw that hungry patients got sicker. ME/CFS care could adopt the same template immediately — the structural barriers are parallel and the screening tools already exist.
